comment_data.body: I can confirm that it's fully working. Amazing work @waninkoko!

I noticed that it worked only one time ... but it didn't work again after that ... can you make sure about that ??

It Do Login But Sending Message / RequestLastSeen Not working

The only thing that's not working is receiving messages that were sent while the client was offline. That's what causes the client to crash when you try to run it after a message has been sent that was not already received when the client was still online.
Fix for now is to run the native client with the same credentials, so that "offline received" messages are sent there, instead of the unofficial client.
@Timvanelsloo I tried to do that but i still can send the message from PHP script but it don't deliver to the other side in IPhone

@waninkoko: 

good job!

i have one question: in the message header, which bit exactly is the encryption flag? If I understand correctly, http://lowlevel-studios.com/whatsapp-protocol-1-2-a-brief-explanation explains the first four bits of the message header are used to store some flags. The first bit of this nibble would be the encryption flag (e.g. 1000b in binary). Is this correct? If my bitwise math is correct, it looks like you set the flag at the fourth bit of the first byte (e.g. 0001 0000b) in flushBuffer():

```
$ret  = $this->writeInt8(isset($this->_key) ? (1 << 4) : 0);
```
(protocol.class.php line 437)

is this intentional, or is any value in the first four bits interpreted as encrypted=true?
Thanks @waninkoko, we'll update the related files later.

@zjorzzzey The flags differ between received and sent nodes.

In sent nodes the encryption flag is the 4th bit (0001 0000), but in received nodes it is the first bit (1000 0000).
Ok, thanks for clarification. It does feel a bit strange (imagine how confusing it gets when they need to use all four flags somewhere in the future) but hey, it works!
